WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:05.200
Hi everyone, thank you so much for being here. My name is Timothy Keyes and I'm a

00:00:05.200 --> 00:00:10.080
data scientist at Stanford HealthCare. Because I work at a hospital, I actually

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:13.560
want to get started by asking you all to remember the last time you went to visit

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:18.200
your doctor. During your appointment, your doctor probably listened to your heart

00:00:18.200 --> 00:00:23.120
as a part of their comprehensive medical exam. They probably also prescribed you

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:28.520
a medication or gave you a vaccine. At some point during your visit, they may

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:33.560
have ordered a laboratory test, like a blood test or an x-ray. And probably at

00:00:33.560 --> 00:00:37.439
some point, someone asked you to update your insurance or billing information

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:42.939
for financial purposes. What you may not know is that at the end of your visit,

00:00:42.939 --> 00:00:46.759
your physician actually wrote up a text document summarizing everything that you

00:00:46.759 --> 00:00:50.240
did together that day and uploaded it into a data system called your

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:56.680
Electronic Health Record, or EHR. Your personal EHR is really important. It's

00:00:56.680 --> 00:01:00.560
basically a story about your health, starting on the day you were born and

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:04.519
leading up to today, that is shared among all of the clinicians who are involved

00:01:04.519 --> 00:01:09.160
in your care. This is useful because it means that the next time you go to see

00:01:09.160 --> 00:01:12.919
one of your doctors, they can reference any of the changes that have happened to

00:01:12.919 --> 00:01:16.239
your medical concerns so that they can offer you the highest quality, most

00:01:16.239 --> 00:01:21.680
efficient care possible when they do see you for what brings you in that day. The

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:26.040
problem with the Electronic Health Record, though, is that over the course of

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:32.360
your entire life, it tends to look less like this and more like this. There are

00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:36.959
thousands of pieces of information about you in your EHR. Every time you've ever

00:01:36.959 --> 00:01:41.040
had your blood pressure taken, every time you've ever filled a prescription, every

00:01:41.040 --> 00:01:45.760
time anyone has interacted with your insurance company, it's so much stuff. So

00:01:45.760 --> 00:01:49.440
it's really hard for your clinician to find any information about you, even when

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:54.919
they're looking for it really hard. This is made even more difficult because, and I

00:01:54.919 --> 00:01:58.559
was kind of shocked to learn this when I was in medical school, is that most of

00:01:58.559 --> 00:02:02.680
this information is stored as unstructured text, making it all the more

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:08.000
difficult to search through and parse. This is why our team at Stanford

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.880
Healthcare created an application called Chat EHR or Chatter. Chatter provides a

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:16.720
chatbot interface for clinicians to ask natural language queries against a

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:21.279
patient's chart and to receive a text answer from an LLM that is hooked into

00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:26.839
the EHR. Chatter's UI is served by an infrastructure layer that handles all

00:02:26.839 --> 00:02:30.399
the technical things that you need when you're working with LLMs, and this

00:02:30.399 --> 00:02:35.679
infrastructure layer is also exposed on the back end as a suite of REST APIs so

00:02:35.679 --> 00:02:40.199
that data scientists like me can build various task-specific automations to

00:02:40.199 --> 00:02:44.160
guide our patients efficiently through the healthcare system. Some of the things

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:48.080
that we tend to do with these task-specific automations are screen

00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:51.679
patients for eligibility for certain kinds of appointments, schedule those

00:02:51.679 --> 00:02:56.240
appointments, and then write draft documentation for our clinicians once

00:02:56.240 --> 00:03:02.240
those appointments are completed. However, this talk is actually not about

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:07.240
Chatter at all. It is not about how it was built, and it is not about how it

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:13.320
works. Instead, it is about a single question that faced our team once we put

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:17.520
this system into production and over 4,000 of our clinicians started using it

00:03:17.919 --> 00:03:23.759
out in the real world for real patient care, and that question is this. How do we

00:03:23.759 --> 00:03:28.279
know that an LLM-powered system is behaving as expected over time, or more

00:03:28.279 --> 00:03:32.399
specifically, how do we know that the text that the LLM is generating is

00:03:32.399 --> 00:03:35.960
reliable, useful, and safe for our patients and the clinicians who serve

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:41.160
them? I can't tell you that our team or really anybody else has definitively

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:44.919
answered this question. It's a really, really hard question, but what I can do

00:03:44.919 --> 00:03:48.559
is share with you three lessons that our organization has learned in our

00:03:48.559 --> 00:03:55.000
journey trying to do so. Sound good? Awesome. This brings us then to lesson

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:01.240
number one, the view from space. I will claim that LLMs really aren't so

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:04.759
different from other statistical models in terms of what you really care about

00:04:04.759 --> 00:04:09.839
organizationally once they have been deployed. What I mean by this is that our

00:04:09.839 --> 00:04:13.679
organization has an MLOps framework that we use for all of our statistical model

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:17.679
deployments, and we were really worried when we started working with LLMs that

00:04:17.679 --> 00:04:20.480
they were just too different of a technology, and they would basically

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:25.799
smash our framework into smithereens and we would have to start over from scratch.

00:04:25.799 --> 00:04:31.399
Luckily, this didn't happen because we just found in practice that regardless

00:04:31.399 --> 00:04:35.760
of the type of model that you're serving, whether it's logistic regression, XGBoost,

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:42.040
an LLM, or an agent, there's always certain things that you have to do to

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:46.200
support a model when it's in production that are kind of regardless of the

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:50.079
underlying technology. Let me illustrate this clearly by walking you through

00:04:50.079 --> 00:04:55.239
Stanford HealthCare's MLOps framework. Your organization probably has something

00:04:55.239 --> 00:04:58.839
pretty similar, but if you don't, Julia Silke actually gave a really beautiful

00:04:58.839 --> 00:05:03.239
talk about MLOps in her PositConf talk a couple of years ago, and you should go

00:05:03.239 --> 00:05:07.839
watch that. But at Stanford HealthCare, we break down MLOps into three pillars.

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:13.079
The first we call system integrity. This is about monitoring a model's ability to

00:05:13.079 --> 00:05:17.480
find its input data and to post its output to the intended destination with low

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:22.519
latency and high availability. This has to do with the IT infrastructure supporting

00:05:22.519 --> 00:05:26.239
your model, so regardless of what that model is, it's always on the table and

00:05:26.239 --> 00:05:31.440
it's something you have to keep track of. The second pillar we call performance.

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:35.239
This is about monitoring the quality and accuracy of the output of the model.

00:05:35.239 --> 00:05:38.920
So how often is the model correct? How often is it incorrect about the things

00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:42.959
that it does or says? Again, regardless of the model, this is something you have to

00:05:42.959 --> 00:05:47.799
care about if you want to be a good data scientist. And then lastly, our third

00:05:47.799 --> 00:05:51.799
pillar is impact. Because we're a hospital, it's really not enough for our

00:05:51.799 --> 00:05:56.760
models to be technically excellent. They also have to have a traceable way of

00:05:56.760 --> 00:06:00.200
serving our number one goal as an organization, which is providing the best

00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:05.359
patient care possible. So we typically also monitor process measures and KPIs

00:06:05.359 --> 00:06:08.880
that are associated with any of our deployments to make sure that they are

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:14.079
serving their intended purpose towards this mission. So we found that these three

00:06:14.079 --> 00:06:18.000
principles, kind of luckily for us, are sufficient for monitoring any model after

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:23.799
it's been deployed, including LLMs. But that all being said, we did find it most

00:06:23.799 --> 00:06:28.959
difficult to tackle this second pillar. How do you define and then monitor the

00:06:28.959 --> 00:06:33.600
accuracy of an LLM? It's a really sophisticated technology, and it can do

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:39.640
so many things. This brings us to our second lesson. So we are now no longer in

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:44.320
space. We have re-entered the atmosphere. And as we get closer to the Earth, we can

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:48.440
appreciate that despite their apparent differences at a high level, there are

00:06:48.440 --> 00:06:52.440
some key differences between LLMs and other kinds of statistical models that

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:57.959
affect how we define and monitor their performance, just like accuracy element.

00:06:57.959 --> 00:07:01.399
There are a bunch of differences that we could pull apart here between LLMs and

00:07:01.399 --> 00:07:04.760
other types of models, but I will talk about three key differences that we are

00:07:04.760 --> 00:07:12.200
most opinionated about at Stanford. The first is this. Humans simply interact

00:07:12.200 --> 00:07:15.559
with text differently than they do with the outputs from other kinds of models,

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:20.640
like probabilities or discrete labels. In a clinical environment, machine learning

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:24.519
models are typically used to make recommendations to clinicians. So they

00:07:24.519 --> 00:07:27.760
might recommend prescribing a particular medication or ordering a

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:32.320
certain laboratory test. But in practice, what we found is that unless these

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:36.720
models are highly, highly accurate, which most of them simply are not, because

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:41.040
medicine is very hard, clinicians learn not to trust them, and so they ignore

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:46.839
them. So they end up being not so useful. With LLMs, on the other hand, we find

00:07:46.839 --> 00:07:50.559
that this kind of like magical human-computer interaction dynamic

00:07:50.559 --> 00:07:54.480
emerges where clinicians are actually really eager to read the free text

00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:59.000
recommendation of an LLM and to understand its justification for making

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.559
that recommendation. They kind of like see what the LLM is suggesting to them,

00:08:02.559 --> 00:08:06.040
run it through their own clinical reasoning process, and then decide if

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:10.959
they agree or disagree with the model. So what we've learned is that monitoring

00:08:10.959 --> 00:08:15.040
the so-called performance of our LLM deployments is really about capturing

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:18.920
this human-in-the-loop adjudication process, so that we can track over time

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:22.799
how much our expert clinicians are agreeing with the things that the LLM

00:08:22.799 --> 00:08:28.399
says. I think this is well illustrated by an example, so I'll walk you through one

00:08:28.399 --> 00:08:33.479
of our LLM deployments to give you a flavor for how this looks in practice.

00:08:33.479 --> 00:08:40.159
The task here is we're asking the LLM to identify patients who might benefit from

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:45.320
an appointment with a specialist, just a certain kind of physician, basically. So

00:08:45.359 --> 00:08:49.760
our starting point is a prompt, and that prompt contains the criteria for the

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:52.840
specialist appointment. It usually contains some information about the

00:08:52.840 --> 00:08:57.919
types of illnesses that the specialist can treat. We send this to the LLM along

00:08:57.919 --> 00:09:01.919
with clinical notes describing the health of the patient and ask the LLM to

00:09:01.919 --> 00:09:06.520
output two things. The first is a targeted recommendation for whether the

00:09:06.520 --> 00:09:10.400
patient should get the specialist appointment, and the second is a

00:09:10.479 --> 00:09:15.359
justification with cited evidence from the patient's chart of why it made that

00:09:15.359 --> 00:09:20.119
recommendation. Both of these are then sent to one of our expert clinicians who

00:09:20.119 --> 00:09:23.440
are always in the loop, and that clinician then decides if they agree or

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:27.080
disagree with the model and if they want to place the referral for the

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:32.479
specialist appointment. Our monitoring approach then really hinges on capturing

00:09:32.479 --> 00:09:36.239
this clinician's decision within our electronic health record, and then we

00:09:36.239 --> 00:09:40.200
track it over time so that if we see basically that the disagreement rate of

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:45.280
our clinicians is increasing for a deployment after some period of

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:48.400
time, this basically suggests that something is going wrong, maybe

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:52.000
documentation practices have changed, maybe we need to adjust the prompt, and

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:58.840
that our data science team then needs to remediate that. Okay, so moving on to our

00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:02.640
second key difference between LLMs and other statistical models in terms of

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:06.679
monitoring performance. Whereas the first one was more conceptual, this one is more

00:10:06.679 --> 00:10:10.640
technical. It has to do with like some engineering things, and it's based on the

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:14.840
observation that frontier LLMs developed by large companies like ChachiPT,

00:10:14.840 --> 00:10:19.280
Claude, and Gemini are externally developed and versioned by third parties.

00:10:19.280 --> 00:10:23.760
So this means that they actually update and deprecate over time without your

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:27.799
team necessarily being in control. This is in contrast to something like an XGBoost

00:10:27.799 --> 00:10:31.479
model that you may have trained, hosted, and served yourself, which will

00:10:31.479 --> 00:10:36.760
only ever be updated or retrained or deprecated, turned off, when you choose.

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:41.580
You may not think about this as being related to monitoring a model

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:45.239
post-deployment in the traditional sense, but my point here is that when you're

00:10:45.239 --> 00:10:50.599
working with proprietary LLMs, you don't just have to worry about the data

00:10:50.599 --> 00:10:54.280
distributions of your deployed population shifting over time, you don't

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:57.760
just have to worry about the user behavior changing over time, you

00:10:57.760 --> 00:11:01.599
actually also have to worry about the model itself changing over time as it's

00:11:01.599 --> 00:11:06.719
continually updated by the third party that has developed it. So what we do

00:11:06.719 --> 00:11:11.159
about this is basically host a suite of internally developed benchmarks that

00:11:11.159 --> 00:11:14.760
help us to monitor task performance for important tasks at Stanford Healthcare

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:19.400
whenever a new model is released. So for those of you who might be familiar, GPT-5

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:23.239
was released a couple of weeks ago, and we were curious like, should we

00:11:23.239 --> 00:11:26.359
switch to this model? We're using a couple of legacy models that won't be

00:11:26.359 --> 00:11:30.039
supported in a couple of months, and so this is our approach for dealing with

00:11:30.039 --> 00:11:35.719
that scenario. For those of you keeping me honest, I have used some jargon here.

00:11:35.719 --> 00:11:42.000
So benchmark is a term that is used commonly in the LLM world, and the LLM

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:45.880
world like really likes jargon, but to keep it short and sweet, a benchmark is

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:50.119
essentially a human-labeled gold-standard test data set for a

00:11:50.119 --> 00:11:55.640
specific task. So if you remember our specialty referral example from before,

00:11:55.640 --> 00:11:58.960
the way that you would generate a benchmark for that is basically taking

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:02.880
your prompts and your clinical notes about a patient, showing them directly to

00:12:02.880 --> 00:12:06.760
a clinician, and then asking, would you place the referral to the specialist for

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:10.640
this patient, yes or no? If you do that for a hundred patients, you've now

00:12:10.640 --> 00:12:13.760
generated a data set that the model never saw during training because it

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:17.719
lives within your walled garden of your databasing of your organization, and

00:12:17.719 --> 00:12:22.599
then you can then use that benchmark to evaluate many different LLMs on that

00:12:22.599 --> 00:12:28.039
task, whether they already exist or if they are released in the future. So what

00:12:28.039 --> 00:12:31.799
we've done in our organization is to basically do this for many different

00:12:31.799 --> 00:12:36.080
tasks that we have identified as high-value, and then bundled them all

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:41.119
together in a custom Python evaluation harness called Medhelm, or medical

00:12:41.119 --> 00:12:45.400
holistic evaluation of language models, that is actually quite similar under the

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:48.359
hood to some of the other evaluation frameworks that have been discussed in

00:12:48.359 --> 00:12:52.799
this session. And in fact, we may end up porting it over to something like

00:12:52.799 --> 00:12:58.719
Inspect in the future. All right, finally, this brings us to our third key

00:12:58.719 --> 00:13:01.479
difference between monitoring LLM performance and monitoring the

00:13:01.479 --> 00:13:04.919
performance of other kinds of statistical models, and this one is the

00:13:04.919 --> 00:13:12.280
hardest. At the end of the day, no matter how big or expansive your

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:16.520
suite of benchmarks is, you just can't evaluate an LLM on every single task

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:19.760
that you could potentially apply it to within your organization. It's not

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:24.440
possible, and even if it were, it'd be prohibitively expensive to do. This

00:13:24.440 --> 00:13:28.320
is because LLM outputs are just so much more flexible and expressive than other

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:32.520
kinds of models that are trained for one or a small number of specific purposes.

00:13:32.520 --> 00:13:36.599
They can take pretty much anything as input, and they can produce pretty

00:13:36.599 --> 00:13:43.799
much anything as output. So what do you do? Our approach is to identify important

00:13:43.840 --> 00:13:47.719
and known failure modes across many of your different LLM deployments and try

00:13:47.719 --> 00:13:51.919
to focus on those. So you basically identify things that you don't want the

00:13:51.919 --> 00:13:56.200
LLM to do, and you monitor those specifically. This is helpful not just

00:13:56.200 --> 00:14:00.880
for monitoring purposes, but it also is kind of a step into a process called

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:04.799
guardrailing your model, which basically means trying to intercept those failure

00:14:04.799 --> 00:14:10.520
modes before they occur. So for example, at our organization, something that we're

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:14.679
really worried about is this issue of LLM hallucinations. Probably many of you

00:14:14.679 --> 00:14:18.880
who work with LLMs are concerned about these as well. In our context, an LLM

00:14:18.880 --> 00:14:23.400
hallucination just means that the model makes a claim about a patient that is

00:14:23.400 --> 00:14:28.520
not substantiated or supported by any of the information present in that

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:33.039
patient's chart. So what we do to monitor this is basically we run automated

00:14:33.039 --> 00:14:38.479
quarto reports that basically conduct a Python analysis using an algorithm

00:14:38.479 --> 00:14:42.799
called fact decomposition, and this estimates the hallucination rate across

00:14:42.799 --> 00:14:47.719
our chatter deployments for us. So how does fact decomposition work? Bear with

00:14:47.719 --> 00:14:54.200
me, it's like an algorithmic talk. You start with the output text

00:14:54.200 --> 00:14:58.799
that an LLM generates, and then you use either natural language processing or

00:14:58.799 --> 00:15:04.599
another LLM to break it into the individual claims that it contains. So

00:15:04.599 --> 00:15:10.080
for example, if the claim or if the output from the LLM says this patient

00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:14.119
came to the neurology clinic to have their headache evaluated, the individual

00:15:14.119 --> 00:15:17.119
claims would be that the patient has a headache and that they went to the

00:15:17.119 --> 00:15:20.440
neurology clinic, and maybe also a third one that's like that their evaluation of

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:24.320
the neurology clinic was about their headache. Once you have these individual

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:28.799
claims, you can then use a powerful reasoning model or a smaller fine-tuned

00:15:28.799 --> 00:15:33.359
language model to cross-reference all of the individual claims with all of the

00:15:33.359 --> 00:15:37.760
clinical notes within the relevant time period of that patient's chart.

00:15:37.760 --> 00:15:42.559
This basically allows you then to flag individual claims that are not supported

00:15:42.559 --> 00:15:47.239
by any of the evidence present in the patient's record, and using simple

00:15:47.239 --> 00:15:51.359
division you can then compute, like estimate a rate at which like how many

00:15:51.359 --> 00:15:56.239
claims or what proportion of claims are supported versus not supported. So as an

00:15:56.239 --> 00:16:01.359
example, this is a plot that I pulled or that I made in plot 9 that I pulled

00:16:01.359 --> 00:16:04.359
from our most recent partial report that ran for the month of August, and

00:16:04.359 --> 00:16:07.400
basically what we're doing is we're estimating the hallucination rates

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:11.159
across our different deployments among three of the different models that we

00:16:11.159 --> 00:16:14.960
route to within the chatter infrastructure. What you can see is that

00:16:14.960 --> 00:16:19.440
one of the models that is becoming a bit dated at this point, GPT-40 mini, was

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:22.679
hallucinating at a much much higher rate than the other models that we were using,

00:16:22.679 --> 00:16:27.039
so this resulted in the recommendation basically to deprecate that model and

00:16:27.039 --> 00:16:33.559
switch to one that was more reliable. Okay, so I would now like to conclude

00:16:33.559 --> 00:16:39.320
with our third and final lesson, the kind of boots-on-the-ground view. When I talk

00:16:39.320 --> 00:16:43.239
to other data scientists about the fact that I mostly work with LLMs now, a

00:16:43.239 --> 00:16:50.440
common, like a common worry that I hear is like, oh I'm really intimidated by LLMs.

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:54.479
I haven't worked with LLMs before and I'm not sure where to get started, but I

00:16:54.520 --> 00:16:59.559
feel like the craze has kind of swept over everybody else, but it forgot me. So

00:16:59.559 --> 00:17:02.559
if there's one thing I would like for you to take away from this talk, it's

00:17:02.559 --> 00:17:06.560
just that as a data scientist, regardless of if you've worked with LLMs before in

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:11.040
the past, you already have all the tools you need to work with LLMs if you would

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:17.439
if you would like. For example, during this talk we've met several components

00:17:17.439 --> 00:17:21.560
of monitoring a deployed LLM system that may have seemed kind of new, but that

00:17:21.560 --> 00:17:25.119
really connect quite deeply to things that you already understand as someone

00:17:25.119 --> 00:17:30.160
that works with statistical systems. For example, we talked about benchmarking,

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:34.680
which just basically is another word for creating a test set for a model that you

00:17:34.680 --> 00:17:38.920
didn't train. You know how to create a test set that's free from bias, that is

00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:42.239
representative of your deployment population, that the model has not seen

00:17:42.239 --> 00:17:47.280
before during training, like none of that is actually new. Secondly, we talked about

00:17:47.280 --> 00:17:51.040
identifying failure modes for a deployment so that you can either

00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:54.760
monitor them specifically or set up guardrails around them. And how do you

00:17:54.760 --> 00:17:59.119
identify these failure modes? Well, it's simple. You spend some time with the logs

00:17:59.119 --> 00:18:02.880
for the tool that you've deployed, do some exploratory data analysis on them,

00:18:02.880 --> 00:18:06.400
and then you work with your governance partners to identify like what are the

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:11.400
problems we really want to avoid here. EDA and governance are foundational in

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:16.400
every single data science workflow, so that's not new either. And then finally

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:21.000
there's this question kind of underlying this entire conversation, which is what

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:25.199
are the tools that I should use to build with LLMs? Unfortunately I can't

00:18:25.199 --> 00:18:28.439
give you a single answer for that. Here are a bunch of the frameworks that I

00:18:28.439 --> 00:18:32.760
have used either in the past or currently. There are many of them, but if

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:37.079
you allow me to give a single recommendation for someone

00:18:37.079 --> 00:18:40.800
who is completely new, I would suggest getting started with the packages that

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:45.040
Posit has developed for building with LLMs. If you work in Python, this is a

00:18:45.040 --> 00:18:49.319
package called chatless. If you work in R, this is a package called Elmer. I think

00:18:49.319 --> 00:18:53.199
what sets these packages apart is just that their docs are so excellent. They

00:18:53.199 --> 00:18:56.520
will teach you everything that you need to know along the way, assuming basically

00:18:56.520 --> 00:19:00.839
no prior knowledge, which is really helpful when you're a beginner. And if

00:19:00.839 --> 00:19:04.319
even that is intimidating, which it very well might be, it certainly was for me

00:19:04.319 --> 00:19:08.280
when I got started, I'll also just leave you with the reminder that there was a

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:12.920
time when the frameworks that we all use every day were new. Dplyr was once new.

00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:18.119
ggplot was once new. Pandas and pullers were once new to us, but if you believe

00:19:18.119 --> 00:19:21.520
in code-first data science, these are skills that you can pick up to help you

00:19:21.520 --> 00:19:27.000
solve problems. So there's no reason to be intimidated. With that, I will thank

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:31.359
you all for being here and invite any questions.

00:19:36.800 --> 00:19:41.880
Thank you, Timothy. We have time for one question and then lunch. And then lunch,

00:19:41.880 --> 00:19:47.359
yeah. Human-in-the-loop accuracy measurement is expensive. How do you do

00:19:47.359 --> 00:19:52.839
this at scale? Yeah, human-in-the-loop is expensive. I mean, you're kind of

00:19:52.839 --> 00:19:56.520
preaching to the choir here because our experts are also clinicians. Like, can you

00:19:56.520 --> 00:19:59.959
imagine the hourly rate for hiring a clinician as a consultant to do

00:19:59.959 --> 00:20:06.760
labeling? Like, whatever number you're thinking of, it's too low. But I

00:20:06.760 --> 00:20:10.239
think the cool thing for us as a health system is we're kind of uniquely

00:20:10.239 --> 00:20:14.160
positioned because all of our users are clinicians, and so if we're giving them

00:20:14.160 --> 00:20:18.199
the tools, we can kind of require them to give us feedback in return. How to do

00:20:18.199 --> 00:20:22.479
this at scale in the general sense, like how to do scale AI for doctors or

00:20:22.479 --> 00:20:27.599
something, I'm not sure. But at least in the medical context, I know that, like, we

00:20:27.599 --> 00:20:30.800
always imagine our deployments as having a human-in-the-loop. We're not doing

00:20:30.800 --> 00:20:34.400
things fully automated, so it's kind of baked into some of the workflows of the

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:37.839
tools we're developing. Sorry for the non-answer, but it's a really hard

00:20:37.839 --> 00:20:43.839
question. Thank you. Let's thank Timothy and all our speakers again.

